The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Srinagar, Jan. 22 (PTI): Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front chairman Mohammad Yasin Malik and four other party leaders were taken into preventive custody ahead of a public meeting in Handwara today.           
	They were detained in a precautionary measure to maintain law and order, police said. Condemning the detention, the party said this was the second time its leaders were prevented from visiting Handwara to meet the people during the past few months. The JKLF organises a number of public meetings across the state but there is no problem of law and order anywhere, said secretary (information) Ashraf-bin-Salam.                   
	 Chandigarh (PTI): The Punjab government has decided to set up a special security group on the lines of the National Security Guard, to counter terrorism and provide quick response in an emergency.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): A former marketing manager of the Hindustan Fertiliser Corporation has been sentenced to three years imprisonment along with a fine of Rs 5 lakh by a CBI court in a disproportionate assets case. Ahmed, during his tenure in 1969-94, had allegedly amassed assets of over Rs 20 lakh.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Gender-based disparities in India have shown a decline over a period of 10 years, according to a government study. The Gender-related Development Index score estimated for India was 0.514 in 1996 and 0.590 in 2006, showing an increase of 0.076 points.                  
	 Vadodara (PTI): Around 500 tribals tilling forest land at Hafeshwar village have been given the right of cultivation under the Forest Rights Act, district collector Vijay Nehra said. They have also been given over 2.5 lakh seedlings free of cost.                  
	 Hyderabad: Abdul Karim Telgi, the prime accused in the fake stamp paper scam, was on Friday sentenced to four years in jail along with five others by a CBI court in Hyderabad.                                                                                                                                              
